, Irsko","Ireland":"Irsko","Kilgarvan, Kerry, Ireland":"Kilgarvan, County Kerry, Irsko"},"da":{"1241–8 Aug 1282":"1241–8. august 1282","1241–1282":"1241–1282","1240–1261":"1240–1261","1261–1298":"1261–1298","1263–Male":"1263–Afdød","1195–1261":"1195–1261","1205–Female":"1205–Afdød","1241":"1241","1263":"1263","1240":"1240","1195":"1195","1261":"1261","1282":"1282","Apr 1261":"april 1261","8 Aug 1282":"8. august 1282","1205":"1205","August 1261":"august 1261","1298":"1298","before 1261":"før 1261","24 July 1261":"24. juli 1261","about 1263":"omkring 1263","Decies, Waterford, Ireland":"Waterford, County Waterford, Irland","County Kerry, Ireland":"County Kerry, Irland","County Limerick, Ireland":"County Limerick, Irland","Ireland":"Irland","Kilgarvan, Kerry, Ireland":"Kilgarvan, County Kerry, Irland"},"nl":{"1241–8 Aug 1282":"1241–8 augustus 1282","1241–1282":"1241–1282","1240–1261":"1240–1261","1261–1298":"1261–1298","1263–Male":"1263–Overleden","1195–1261":"1195–1261","1205–Female":"1205–Overleden","1241":"1241","1263":"1263","1240":"1240","1195":"1195","1261":"1261","1282":"1282","Apr 1261":"april 1261","8 Aug 1282":"8 augustus 1282","1205":"1205","August 1261":"augustus 1261","1298":"1298","before 1261":"vóór 1261","24 July 1261":"24 juli 1261","about 1263":"circa 1263","Decies, Waterford, Ireland":"Waterford, County Waterford, Ierland","County Kerry, Ireland":"County Kerry, Ierland","County Limerick, Ireland":"County Limerick, Ierland","Ireland":"Ierland","Kilgarvan, Kerry, Ireland":"Kilgarvan, County Kerry, Ierland"},"en":{"1241–8 Aug 1282":"1241–8 August 1282","1241–1282":"1241–1282","1240–1261":"1240–1261","1261–1298":"1261–1298","1263–Male":"1263–Deceased","1195–1261":"1195–1261","1205–Female":"1205–Deceased","1241":"1241","1263":"1263","1240":"1240","1195":"1195","1261":"1261","1282":"1282","Apr 1261":"April 1261","8 Aug 1282":"8 August 1282","1205":"1205","August 1261":"August 1261","1298":"1298","before 1261":"before 1261","24 July 1261":"24 July 1261","about 1263":"about 1263","Decies, Waterford, Ireland":"Waterford, County Waterford, Ireland","County Kerry, Ireland":"County Kerry, Ireland","County Limerick, Ireland":"County Limerick, Ireland","Ireland":"Ireland","Kilgarvan, Kerry, Ireland":"Kilgarvan, County Kerry, Ireland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Barry","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Donal, Aidan, Ciaran, Eoin, John Patrick, Kaitlin, Kieran, Murphy, Aileen, Brigid, Caitlin.","Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Beargha</b> ‘descendant of <i>Beargh</i>’, a byname meaning ‘plunderer’.","Irish and Manx: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Báire</b> ‘descendant of <i>Báire</i>’, a short form of either of two Gaelic personal names, <i>Bairrfhionn</i> or <i>Fionnbharr</i>, both meaning ‘fair-topped’. This may also be the source of the Manx name <i>Barry</i>, whose family's main seat was Ballavarry in Kirk Andreas."],"variants":[{"name":"Barr","meanings":["Scottish (Glasgow) and northern Irish (Ulster): habitational name from any of various places in southwestern Scotland, in particular Ayrshire and Renfrewshire, named with Gaelic <i>barr</i> ‘height, hill’ or a Brittonic cognate of this.","English and Welsh: habitational name from Great Barr in Staffordshire. This is from Brittonic <i>barro-</i> ‘top, summit’, referring to Barr Beacon; there is evidence that this was known as <i>la Bare</i> in the 13th century.","English (of Norman origin): habitational name from Barre-en-Ouche in Eure, France, or perhaps from Barre-de-Semilly in Manche, France."]},{"name":"Barrie","meanings":["Scottish (Angus): habitational name from Barry in Angus or from another place so named, generally named with Gaelic <i>barr</i> ‘height, hill’, or from a British cognate of this word. This name is also the Scottish form of   Barry  .","French (<b>Barrié</b>): variant of   Barrier  .","Altered form of French   Baril  . Compare   Barry   7."]},{"name":"Berry","meanings":["Irish and Manx: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Béara</b> ‘descendant of <i>Béara</i>’, a personal name of unexplained etymology; or, in some cases, perhaps an Anglicized form of Irish and Manx <b>Ó Beargha</b>. Compare   Barry   1.","Scottish and northern Irish: variant of   Barrie  .","English: habitational name from any of several places called in Devon named with Old English <i>byrig</i>, dative case of <i>burh</i> ‘fortified manor house, stronghold’, such as Berry Pomeroy and Berrynarbor."]},{"name":"Dubarry","meanings":["French: variant of the topographic or habitational name   Barry  , with fused preposition and definite article <i>du</i> ‘from the’."]},{"name":"Baril","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Marcel, Andre, Normand, Alain, Armand, Ghislaine, Jacques, Jean-Marc, Jean-Pierre, Lucien, Monique, Phillippe.","French: from Old French <i>baril</i> ‘barrel’, applied as a metonymic occupational name for a cooper, or a nickname for a rotund man. Compare   Barry   7 and   Berry   7.","History: Jean Baril from the Saintonge region of France was in QC by 1673, when he married Marie Guillet, the first of his three wives. He died in 1724 in Batiscan, QC. His descendants also bear altered forms of the surname, such as <i>Barrie</i>, <i>Bar(r)y</i>, and <i>Berry</i>."]},{"name":"Bary","meanings":["Walloon and northern French: variant of   Barry   8.","French (southern): rare variant of   Barry   6.","Altered form of French   Baril  . Compare   Barry   7."]}]},{"name":"Maud","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Medieval vernacular form of   Matilda .  This form was characteristically Low German (i.e. including medieval Dutch and Flemish). The wife of  William the Conqueror , who bore this name, was the daughter of  Baldwin , Count of Flanders. In Flemish and Dutch the letter <i>-t-</i> was generally lost when it occurred between vowels, giving forms such as <i>Ma(h)auld</i>. <i>Maud</i> or <i>Matilda</i> was also the name of the daughter (  1102–67 ) of  Henry I  of England; she was married early in life to the Holy Roman Emperor  Henry V , and later disputed the throne of England with her cousin  Stephen . In  1128  she married  Geoffrey , Count of Anjou. A medieval chronicler commented, ‘she was a good woman, but she had little bliss with him’. The name <i>Maud</i> became quite common in England in the 19th century, when its popularity was influenced in part by  Tennyson's  poem Maud, published in  1855 , but has not been much used since the early decades of the 20th century."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Maud de Barry was born in 1241, in Ireland, her father, David De Barry I, was 46 and her mother, Mabel LeBotiller, was 36. She married Maurice Fitz John Lord of Decies and Desmond before 1261, in Ireland. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. She died on 8 August 1282, in her hometown, at the age of 41."},"et":{"1241–8 Aug 1282":"1241–8. august 1282","1241–1282":"1241–1282","1240–1261":"1240–1261","1261–1298":"1261–1298","1263–Male":"1263–Surnud","1195–1261":"1195–1261","1205–Female":"1205–Surnud","1241":"1241","1263":"1263","1240":"1240","1195":"1195","1261":"1261","1282":"1282","Apr 1261":"